Wellness Tourism Package: Development of strategies to identify and expand customer base¶

Introduction¶

The 'Visit with us' company has a new product called "Wellness Tourism Package". The package will offer a path to the customer to increase their well-being by giving the ability to kick-start a healthy lifestyle, or enhance their current lifestyle, or assist in maintaining their current healthy lifestyle. The current aim is to expand the customer base by building a viable business model that includes the new product as a path forward.

Background: The company offered 5 tourism packages earlier: Basic, Standard, Deluxe, Super Deluxe, King. The marketing campaign contacted customers at random with no prior analysis. This resulted in 18% of customers buying the packages, however, the marketing cost was high.

Objective¶

  1. Identifying potential customers who are likely to purchase the Wellness Tourism Package.
  2. Generating insights into the characteristics of the customers that would optimize the marketing team's strategies.

Data Information/Variables¶

CustomerID - the unqiue customer ID
ProdTaken - has value 0/1: customer has not/has purchased a package
Age - age of customer
TypeofContact - company invited or customer did self inquiry
CityTier - describes development/facilities/population of city.There are three ordered tiers, Tier 1> Tier 2 > Tier 3.
Occupation - occupation of customer
Gender - the gender of the customer
NumberOfPersonVisiting - number of people taking the trip with customer
PreferredProptertyStar - preferred hotel rating by customer
MaritalStatus - marital status of the customer
NumberOfTrips - Average number of trips in year by customer
Passport - 0/1 data: customer does not have/has passport
OwnCar - 0/1 data: customer does not have/has a car
NumberOfChildrenVisting - total number of children with age less than 5 who are planning to take the trip with the customer
Designation - designation of the customer in their current organization
MonthlyIncome - gross monthly income of the customer
DurationOfPitch - duration of the pitch by salesperson to customer
ProductPitched - product pitched by the salesperson
PitchSatisfactionScore - the sales pitch satisfaction score
NumberOfFollowups - total number of follow-ups that were done by the sales person after the initial pitch

# Converting the "Gender" column so that it has 2 unique values (Male,Female)
# We are writing a user-defined function. The description of the function is in the document string.
def gender_fix(gender_val):
    """This function takes Gender as the input, determines whether the value is "Fe Male" and returns it as "Female"."""
    if isinstance(gender_val, str):  # to check if the gender observation is a string
        if gender_val.startswith("Fe "):  # checks if the value starts with "Fe "
            return str(gender_val.replace("Fe Male", "Female"))
        else:
            return gender_val


customerData1["Gender"] = customerData1["Gender"].apply(gender_fix)

Observations for customer profile¶

Based on the EDA analysis, we can conclude that the customer base has high interest in making self-inquiries for travel packages (though this does not always translate to buying a package). They also mostly do not own a passport, but do own a car. A significant portion of the customer base lives in Tier 1 cities - these are cities that have population/facilities. They also prefer 3 star properties, and can be into small business owners or salaried personannel as well. They are also male, younger customers who take 2-3 trips on average per year and the basic package appeals to them.

# functions to treat outliers by flooring and capping


def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    Treats outliers in a variable

    df: dataframe
    col: dataframe column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    """
    Treat outliers in a list of variables

    df: dataframe
    col_list: list of dataframe columns
    """
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c)

    return df
In [168]:

8. Bagging models¶

This section will have: decision tree, bagging classifier, random forest. All three types will have: (a) model building, (b) performance evaluation (c) model improvement with hypertuning.

Note about model predictions¶

The ProdTaken column is the dependent variable. We are trying to predict which customers in the dataset would buy a travel package with "Visit with Us". So, we are attempting to predict which of the customers from the test data set will have ProdTaken = 1 or ProdTaken = 0.
We will use recall and F1 as our most important performance measures.
The wrong predictions will consist of (a) the customer was predicted to buy a travel package, but did not when the marketing campaign targeted that customer (False Positive) and (b) the customer was predicted to not buy a travel package, but ended up buying a travel package (False negative).
In terms of cost and resources, the false positives (prediction of ProdTaken = 1) will be more important since the marketing campaign will cost money and resources, and the predictions will drive strategy and revenue forecasts for the travel company as well.

# This will calculate the performance measures for classification model
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [181]:
#This function will build the confusion matrix 
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Training performance comparision for above models¶

Observations¶

Despite being vastly different than the training set (where it is overfitting), the hypertuned random forest tree manages a 71.3% recall, 92.9% precision and a 80.7% F1 score. Accuracy is 93.5%. Thus, this model has the best performance scores among the bagging models and decision tree. A false positive rate of 1.02% on the test set indicates that for every 100 customers the model predicted to buy the package, one person ended up not buying thus resulting in a favorable recall score (which is biggest indicator of false positives). The F1 is the harmonic mean between recall and precision and will always lie between recall and F1, and is thus 80% in this case.

## Function to create confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(model, y_actual, labels=[1, 0]):
    """
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth

    """
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(
        cm,
        index=[i for i in ["Actual - No", "Actual - Yes"]],
        columns=[i for i in ["Predicted - No", "Predicted - Yes"]],
    )
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cm.flatten() / np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in zip(group_counts, group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2, 2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

##  Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall and Precision
def get_metrics_score(model, flag=True):
    """
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    """
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    score_list = []

    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    train_acc = model.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_acc = model.score(X_test, y_test)

    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_train, pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test, pred_test)

    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train, pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test, pred_test)
    
    train_F1 = metrics.f1_score(y_train, pred_train)
    test_F1 = metrics.f1_score(y_test, pred_test)

    score_list.extend(
        (
            train_acc,
            test_acc,
            train_recall,
            test_recall,
            train_precision,
            test_precision,
            train_F1,
            test_F1
        )
    )

    # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed. The default value is set to True.
    if flag == True:
        print("Accuracy on training set : ", model.score(X_train, y_train))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ", model.score(X_test, y_test))
        print("Recall on training set : ", metrics.recall_score(y_train, pred_train))
        print("Recall on test set : ", metrics.recall_score(y_test, pred_test))
        print(
            "Precision on training set : ", metrics.precision_score(y_train, pred_train)
        )
        print("Precision on test set : ", metrics.precision_score(y_test, pred_test))
        print(
            "F1 on training set : ", metrics.f1_score(y_train, pred_train)
        )
        print("F1 on test set : ", metrics.f1_score(y_test, pred_test))

    return score_list  # returning the list with train and test scores

Between the boosting models, the XGBoost gave the best train-test accuracy performance. For recall, the XGBoost tuned gave the best recall on the testing set (81%). Our most important measures are recall and F1 - so from boosting - the models that had a reasonable performance was the tuned XGBoost.
Between the bagging section and boosting section, the random forest estimator (recall = 71.3%, precision = 92.9%, F1 = 80.77% on testing set) compares well to the XGBoost tuned (recall = 81%, precision = 72%, F1 = 72%).
Overall, for an imbalanced data set - where only 18% of the data had ProdTaken = 1, influenced the models on how well they performed on recall and precision and F1.
If we consider recall to be most important measure, then XGBoost tuned gave a high metric for recall (81%). If both recall and F1 are considered to be most important measure, then the tuned random forest performed better since it had an F1 of 80.77%.

10. Insights and recommendations¶

  1. Majority of the customer base is highly interested in tourism packages - given that 70.4% made a self enquiry about travel packages on their own. This indicates that if the right sort of travel package is offered to these customers, the likelihood that they will purchase a travel package is good.
  2. 82% of the customers who did a self enquiry and 78% of the customers who were contacted by the company did not purchase a tourism package. This indicates that either the packages did not appeal to the customers or they could not afford the travel packages.
  3. While Deluxe was the package that was pitched the most to customers, the Basic package was the one that was purchased most of the time. This indicates that there is a mismatch between what is being offered to the customer and what they actually want/or can afford.
  4. The model predictions gave importance to monthly income and age and duration of pitch - hence, the marketing team can target customers based on their income (higher income bracket should be targeted more often) and age (younger customers for basic package). In addition, the duration of pitch can also influence whether the customer will ultimately buy the package or not, so the marketing department should strategize on how to engage the customer for an optimum duration while pitching the package product to them.
  5. Overall, the potential to market a wellness tourism package is present - especially since the customer base is mostly manager designation or above (which involves long hours and stress, so a wellness package may seem attractive). However, since the customers prefer 3 star properties, and domestic locations, as well are in the younger age bracket - the wellness packages should incorporate these features into the product.
